:::summary
The American Revolution (1765–1783) was both a political rebellion against British imperial rule and a philosophical revolution grounded in a rich synthesis of classical republican thought, Christian natural law theology, and Enlightenment political philosophy. The revolutionary generation was arguably the most classically educated political leadership any modern republic has ever had — men who read Cicero, Thucydides, Plutarch, and Livy alongside their Bibles and Locke, and who deliberately modeled their republic on the best elements of Greek and Roman experience. Understanding the Revolution requires understanding this deep classical and Christian inheritance.
